            . I live in <placeName id="t18310217-193-crimeloc1159">Newton-street, Holborn</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-193-crimeloc1159" type="placeName" value="Newton-street, Holborn"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-193-crimeloc1159" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-193-off1157 t18310217-193-crimeloc1159"></join>. The prisoner was in my employ, as <rs id="t18310217-193-deflabel1160" type="occupation">household-servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-193-defend1867 t18310217-193-deflabel1160"></join>, for eighteen months; I had for a long time missed wine from my private wine-cellar, and on the 10th of January, when I went to get some brandy, I missed a quantity of that; I missed wine every time I went - I asked<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183102170112"></xptr>my son if he had taken any; he said No - he then came down into the cellar, and we laid a plan to detect the thief, by putting this detonating snap; some of the wine was twenty-four years old, and some ten years old - when I returned to town the next morning the prisoner, who had been detected, said he had taken the wine, and drank it, broken the bottles, and thrown them with the other broken bottles; I had lost a key of the cellar for six months.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-193-person1871">
                  WILLIAM 
                  SPENCER
               <interp inst="t18310217-193-person1871" type="surname" value="SPENCER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-193-person1871" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-193-person1871" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I knew of the snap having been put on the door, and about half-past eight o'clock in the evening on the 11th of January, I heard the prisoner go across the warehouse, and down to the wine-cellar - I heard the snap go off, and I went down and took him; he denied then that he had taken any wine, but the next morning he said he had taken it, and drank it - Mr. Spencer has lost not less than six dozen of wine, besides brandy.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. His son is cohabiting with a lady in Burton-crescent, and he had been in the habit of sending wine there - I have been afraid to say any thing, because he acted as a sort of deputy master over me; they let me go home that night, and then took me the next morning - they got two men there to frighten me, and asked if I knew of any body else being guilty.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18310217-193-verdict1161" type="verdictDescription">
